#. type: Plain text
#: origin/nameif.txt:12
msgid ""
"DESCRIPTION: This hint describes how to specify your own names for Network "
"Interface Cards instead of eth0, eth1, etc..."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/nameif.txt:17
msgid ""
"PREREQUISITES: In principle the hint applies to all versions of LFS, and "
"probably also to all LINUX distributions.  However, the bootscript "
"recommendations are based on LFS-Bootscripts-1.11 (LFS-4.1)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/nameif.txt:19
msgid "HINT:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/nameif.txt:21
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Introduction\n"
"============\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/nameif.txt:30
msgid ""
"When the Linux kernel boots, it assigns names (eth0 etc..) to network "
"devices in the order that it finds them.  This means that two different "
"versions of the kernel, say 2.4 and 2.6, might find the network interfaces "
"in a diffent order.  When this happens you might have to swap all the cables "
"to get your connections to work the way you want.  The proper way to do this "
"is to name the interfaces with the nameif command (part of the net-tools)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/nameif.txt:32
msgid "TAKE CARE: All the commands given in this hint need root priviledges."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/nameif.txt:34
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"MACTAB and NAMEIF\n"
"=================\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/nameif.txt:40
msgid ""
"The nameif command can be driven from the command line, if you want to do "
"that, then read it's man page.  Another way is to set up a /etc/mactab file "
"to relate the MAC addresses of the network cards to the names you want."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/nameif.txt:44
msgid ""
"Every NIC interface in the (known) universe has a unique MAC address (Media "
"Access Control address), which is usually expressed as a 12 digit "
"hexadecimal number, colon-dotted in pairs for readability."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/nameif.txt:49
msgid ""
"You will need to find the MAC addresses of each of your network cards.  The "
"easiest way to find these (if you didn't make a note of the MAC label when "
"you installed the card) is to use ifconfig, each interface that is "
"configured will report its MAC address.  e.g:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/nameif.txt:59
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ /sbin/ifconfig\n"
"eth0      Link encap:Ethernet  HWaddr 00:60:97:52:9A:94  \n"
"          inet addr:192.168.1.3  Bcast:192.168.1.255  Mask:255.255.255.0\n"
"          UP BROADCAST RUNNING MULTICAST  MTU:1500  Metric:1\n"
"          RX packets:6043 errors:0 dropped:0 overruns:0 frame:0\n"
"          TX packets:6039 errors:0 dropped:0 overruns:0 carrier:0\n"
"          collisions:0 txqueuelen:100 \n"
"          RX bytes:1439604 (1.3 Mb)  TX bytes:509857 (497.9 Kb)\n"
"          Interrupt:10 Base address:0xc800 \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/nameif.txt:67
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"lo        Link encap:Local Loopback  \n"
"          inet addr:127.0.0.1  Mask:255.0.0.0\n"
"          UP LOOPBACK RUNNING  MTU:16436  Metric:1\n"
"          RX packets:7218 errors:0 dropped:0 overruns:0 frame:0\n"
